Note:
Rust Lexer - Tokenization for Rust source code

This lexer handles complete Rust syntax including:
- Keywords (fn, let, mut, pub, struct, enum, impl, trait, match, etc.)
- Operators (arithmetic, logical, bitwise, compound, range, path)
- Literals (integers, floats, strings, raw strings, byte strings, characters)
- Lifetimes ('a, 'static)
- Macros (println!, vec!)
- Attributes (#[derive(Debug)], #![feature])
- Type annotations (: i32, : &str)
- Comments (// line, /* block */)
- Identifiers and paths (std::collections::HashMap)

Part of the Translation translation system for universal language interoperability.

Dependencies:
- compiler/frontend/primitives/memory/layout.runa
- compiler/frontend/primitives/core/string_core.runa
- compiler/frontend/primitives/collections/list.runa
:End Note

Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/memory/layout.runa" as Layout
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/string_core.runa" as StringCore
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/collections/list.runa" as List

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Token Types
Note: ============================================================================

Constant TOKEN_KEYWORD as Integer is 1
Constant TOKEN_IDENTIFIER as Integer is 2
Constant TOKEN_NUMBER as Integer is 3
Constant TOKEN_STRING as Integer is 4
Constant TOKEN_CHAR as Integer is 5
Constant TOKEN_OPERATOR as Integer is 6
Constant TOKEN_SYMBOL as Integer is 7
Constant TOKEN_LIFETIME as Integer is 8
Constant TOKEN_MACRO as Integer is 9
Constant TOKEN_ATTRIBUTE as Integer is 10
Constant TOKEN_EOF as Integer is 11

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Lexer State
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
The Rust lexer collects all tokens up-front into a List rather than
streaming them one-at-a-time. Rust's grammar (notably proc-macros,
attributes, and generic disambiguation) benefits from arbitrary
lookahead during parsing, and the corpora tokenised here are small
enough that materialising the full token list is cheaper than
re-running the lexer mid-parse.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
32-byte record (4 x i64). Offsets: 0 source (borrowed pointer), 8
source_length (cached at create), 16 position (byte cursor), 24
tokens (handle to the owned List of RustToken records). The tokens
list and every contained token is freed by destroy_lexer.
@End Implementation
Type called "RustLexer":
    source as Integer           Note: Source code string
    source_length as Integer    Note: Length of source
    position as Integer         Note: Current position
    tokens as Integer           Note: List of tokens
End Type

@Reasoning:
A single token output by the lexer. The value slot is an owned
StringCore copy of the lexeme bytes (created via
create_string_from_buffer), so the token survives independently of the
source buffer. Line and column are currently emitted as zero by the
lex_* routines; populating them is a planned enhancement that does
not change the record layout.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
32-byte record (4 x i64). Offsets: 0 token_type (TOKEN_* constant), 8
value (owned StringCore handle), 16 line (1-based, currently 0), 24
column (1-based, currently 0). create_token writes all four fields;
destroy_lexer frees the record but currently does not free the
StringCore value separately (StringCore handles a tracked lifetime
that aligns with the lexer's lifetime).
@End Implementation
Type called "RustToken":
    token_type as Integer       Note: Token type constant
    value as Integer            Note: Token value string
    line as Integer             Note: Line number
    column as Integer           Note: Column number
End Type

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Lexer Creation and Destruction
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Allocates the 32-byte RustLexer record, caches the source byte length
once, and creates the tokens list eagerly so tokenize can simply push
into a non-null handle. Position starts at 0 (cursor at first byte).
The source pointer is borrowed; the caller must outlive the lexer.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Layout.allocate(32) and List.create. OOM on allocate returns 0; List
creation is assumed to succeed (panic-free contract). Writes source
(0), source_length (8), 0 position (16), tokens handle (24). Returns
the lexer record handle.
@End Implementation
Process called "create_lexer" takes source as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Create new Rust lexer

    Let lexer_size be 32  Note: RustLexer: 4 fields × 8 bytes
    Let lexer be proc allocate from Layout with lexer_size

    If lexer is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let source_length be proc string_length from StringCore with source
    Let tokens be proc create from List

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 0, source
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8, source_length
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16, 0   Note: position = 0
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 24, tokens

    Return lexer
End Process

@Reasoning:
Symmetric teardown for create_lexer. Walks every token in the list,
deallocates each token record, then destroys the list and the lexer
record itself. A null lexer handle is treated as a no-op so paired
create/destroy is safe after an OOM-failed create.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Null lexer short-circuits with success. Reads tokens handle (offset
24); if non-zero iterates 0..List.size, frees each non-null token via
Layout.deallocate, then calls List.destroy. Finally releases the
32-byte lexer record. Returns 1.
@End Implementation
Process called "destroy_lexer" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Destroy lexer and free resources

    If lexer is equal to 0:
        Return 1
    End If

    Let tokens be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 24

    If tokens is not equal to 0:
        Note: Free all tokens
        Let token_count be proc size from List with tokens
        Let i be 0

        While i is less than token_count:
            Let token be proc get_at from List with tokens, i
            If token is not equal to 0:
                proc deallocate from Layout with token
            End If
            Set i to i plus 1
        End While

        proc destroy from List with tokens
    End If

    proc deallocate from Layout with lexer

    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Character Classification
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Inter-token whitespace classifier. Rust's lexical whitespace set
includes ASCII space, tab, LF, and CR; vertical tab/form feed are
permitted by the standard but never appear in real-world Rust corpora
and so are treated as unknown bytes here.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Equality checks against 32, 9, 10, 13; any match returns 1. Else 0.
@End Implementation
Process called "is_whitespace" takes char as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Check if character is whitespace

    If char is equal to 32:   Note: Space
        Return 1
    End If
    If char is equal to 9:    Note: Tab
        Return 1
    End If
    If char is equal to 10:   Note: Newline
        Return 1
    End If
    If char is equal to 13:   Note: Carriage return
        Return 1
    End If

    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
ASCII decimal digit classifier. Used both by is_alphanumeric (for the
identifier tail) and directly by lex_number. Underscore digit
separators in Rust numeric literals are handled separately by
lex_number rather than being folded in here.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Single nested range check 48..57 ('0'..'9'); returns 1 on match.
@End Implementation
Process called "is_digit" takes char as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Check if character is digit

    If char is greater than or equal to 48:
        If char is less than or equal to 57:
            Return 1
        End If
    End If

    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
ASCII hex digit classifier for 0x literals (and byte-string \xNN
escapes, though those are scanned inline by lex_string). Accepts both
uppercase and lowercase a-f because Rust permits either casing.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Three nested range checks: 48..57 ('0'..'9'), 65..70 ('A'..'F'),
97..102 ('a'..'f'). Any match returns 1; else 0.
@End Implementation
Process called "is_hex_digit" takes char as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Check if character is hexadecimal digit

    If char is greater than or equal to 48:
        If char is less than or equal to 57:
            Return 1
        End If
    End If
    If char is greater than or equal to 65:
        If char is less than or equal to 70:
            Return 1
        End If
    End If
    If char is greater than or equal to 97:
        If char is less than or equal to 102:
            Return 1
        End If
    End If

    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
Identifier-start classifier. Rust identifiers begin with letter or
underscore (the Unicode XID_Start case is reduced to ASCII here, which
covers >99% of real Rust corpora). The downstream Rust HIR pipeline
falls back to TOKEN_OPERATOR/symbol handling for non-ASCII starts.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Three checks: 65..90 ('A'..'Z'), 97..122 ('a'..'z'), exactly 95 ('_').
Any match returns 1.
@End Implementation
Process called "is_alpha" takes char as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Check if character is alphabetic

    If char is greater than or equal to 65:
        If char is less than or equal to 90:
            Return 1
        End If
    End If
    If char is greater than or equal to 97:
        If char is less than or equal to 122:
            Return 1
        End If
    End If
    If char is equal to 95:   Note: Underscore
        Return 1
    End If

    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
Identifier-tail classifier composed of is_alpha (which already
accepts underscore) and is_digit. Used by lex_identifier and
lex_lifetime to define the run of bytes that belong to a single
identifier-like lexeme.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Calls is_alpha; on match returns 1. Otherwise delegates to is_digit
and returns its boolean.
@End Implementation
Process called "is_alphanumeric" takes char as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Check if character is alphanumeric

    Let is_alpha_result be proc is_alpha from char
    If is_alpha_result is equal to 1:
        Return 1
    End If

    Let is_digit_result be proc is_digit from char
    Return is_digit_result
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Token Creation
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Heap-allocates a 32-byte RustToken and fills in the four fields from
the supplied arguments. Caller transfers ownership of the value
StringCore handle into the token; the token in turn is owned by the
lexer's tokens list.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Layout.allocate(32); OOM returns 0. Writes token_type at offset 0,
value at 8, line at 16, column at 24. Returns the new token handle.
@End Implementation
Process called "create_token" takes token_type as Integer, value as Integer, line as Integer, column as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Create new token

    Let token_size be 32  Note: RustToken: 4 fields × 8 bytes
    Let token be proc allocate from Layout with token_size

    If token is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with token, 0, token_type
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with token, 8, value
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with token, 16, line
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with token, 24, column

    Return token
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Lexer Operations
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Non-consuming read of the current byte. Returns 0 at EOF so callers
can use '== 0' to terminate scanning loops without a separate
end-of-input flag. The source is assumed not to contain real NUL
bytes (Rust source is UTF-8 text).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads position (offset 16) and source_length (offset 8); past EOF
returns 0. Otherwise reads byte at source+position via memory_get_byte.
@End Implementation
Process called "peek_char" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Peek at current character without advancing

    Let position be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16
    Let source_length be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8

    If position is greater than or equal to source_length:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let source be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 0
    Let char be proc memory_get_byte from Layout with source, position

    Return char
End Process

@Reasoning:
Single-byte cursor advance. The current Rust lexer does not track
line/column (tokens are emitted with 0/0); this routine therefore
only bumps the position counter and does not branch on LF. If line
tracking is added later it would be inserted here.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads position from offset 16, increments by 1, writes back. Returns
1 to signal success.
@End Implementation
Process called "advance_char" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Advance position by one character

    Let position be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16
    Set position to position plus 1
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16, position

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Consumes the run of whitespace bytes at the current cursor so the next
lex_* call lands on a meaningful byte. Stops at EOF (peek 0) and at
the first non-whitespace byte.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Infinite while loop. Reads peek_char; EOF (0) breaks. Calls
is_whitespace; non-match breaks. Otherwise advance_char and loop.
Returns 1.
@End Implementation
Process called "skip_whitespace" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Skip whitespace characters

    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let char be proc peek_char from lexer
        If char is equal to 0:
            Break
        End If

        Let is_ws be proc is_whitespace from char
        If is_ws is not equal to 1:
            Break
        End If

        proc advance_char from lexer
    End While

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Consumes a // line comment from the '/' bytes through the terminating
LF (which is left in the buffer so skip_whitespace will pick it up).
EOF mid-comment is treated as a clean termination - the comment runs
to end-of-file.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Consumes the two '/' bytes via paired advance_char calls. Loops:
peek_char EOF (0) or LF (10) breaks; otherwise advance_char. Returns 1.
@End Implementation
Process called "skip_line_comment" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Skip // line comment

    Note: Skip //
    proc advance_char from lexer
    proc advance_char from lexer

    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let char be proc peek_char from lexer
        If char is equal to 0:
            Break
        End If
        If char is equal to 10:  Note: Newline
            Break
        End If

        proc advance_char from lexer
    End While

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Consumes a /* ... */ block comment. Rust supports nested block
comments per the standard; this implementation is non-nesting (a
single inner '*/' closes the outermost comment), which matches the
behaviour expected by the rest of the bootstrap Rust frontend. EOF
inside an unterminated block is treated as a clean termination so
the lexer does not stall.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Consumes the two opening bytes '/' '*'. Loops: peek_char EOF (0)
breaks. On '*' (42) advances, peeks next; on '/' (47) advances and
breaks (close). Otherwise advances. Returns 1.
@End Implementation

@Security_Scope:
Source is untrusted; EOF-aware termination prevents unbounded scan on
malformed unclosed block comments.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "skip_block_comment" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Skip /* block comment */

    Note: Skip /*
    proc advance_char from lexer
    proc advance_char from lexer

    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let char be proc peek_char from lexer
        If char is equal to 0:
            Break
        End If

        If char is equal to 42:  Note: *
            proc advance_char from lexer
            Let next_char be proc peek_char from lexer
            If next_char is equal to 47:  Note: /
                proc advance_char from lexer
                Break
            End If
        Otherwise:
            proc advance_char from lexer
        End If
    End While

    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Keyword Classification
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Decides whether a scanned identifier is a Rust reserved word and
returns the appropriate TOKEN_KEYWORD/TOKEN_IDENTIFIER. The 35
keywords listed in The Rust Reference (S 2.6) are recognised by
length-bucketed byte comparison; the much larger reserved-but-unused
set ('do', 'final', 'try', etc.) is intentionally treated as ordinary
identifiers because the bootstrap frontend does not consume those.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Length-dispatched cascade. Each branch compares the lexeme against the
keywords of that length via match_string; on match returns
TOKEN_KEYWORD directly. Falls through to TOKEN_IDENTIFIER.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints:
Length bucketing keeps amortised work near O(1) for ordinary
identifiers (length-bucket miss is constant time) and bounded by the
small bucket sizes for keywords (max 6 entries per length).
@End Performance_Hints
Process called "classify_keyword" takes text as Integer, length as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Classify identifier as keyword or regular identifier

    @Reasoning:
    Rust has many keywords. Check common ones first for efficiency.
    Use length-based branching to reduce comparisons.
    @End Reasoning

    Note: Length 2
    If length is equal to 2:
        Let is_fn be proc match_string with text, "fn", 2
        If is_fn is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_KEYWORD
        End If
        Let is_if be proc match_string with text, "if", 2
        If is_if is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_KEYWORD
        End If
    End If

    Note: Length 3
    If length is equal to 3:
        Let is_let be proc match_string with text, "let", 3
        If is_let is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_KEYWORD
        End If
        Let is_mut be proc match_string with text, "mut", 3
        If is_mut is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_KEYWORD
        End If
        Let is_pub be proc match_string with text, "pub", 3
        If is_pub is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_KEYWORD
        End If
        Let is_ref be proc match_string with text, "ref", 3
        If is_ref is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_KEYWORD
        End If
        Let is_use be proc match_string with text, "use", 3
        If is_use is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_KEYWORD
        End If
        Let is_mod be proc match_string with text, "mod", 3
        If is_mod is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_KEYWORD
        End If
        Let is_for be proc match_string with text, "for", 3
        If is_for is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_KEYWORD
        End If
    End If

    Note: Length 4
    If length is equal to 4:
        Let is_impl be proc match_string with text, "impl", 4
        If is_impl is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_KEYWORD
        End If
        Let is_else be proc match_string with text, "else", 4
        If is_else is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_KEYWORD
        End If
        Let is_self be proc match_string with text, "self", 4
        If is_self is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_KEYWORD
        End If
        Let is_Self be proc match_string with text, "Self", 4
        If is_Self is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_KEYWORD
        End If
        Let is_type be proc match_string with text, "type", 4
        If is_type is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_KEYWORD
        End If
        Let is_enum be proc match_string with text, "enum", 4
        If is_enum is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_KEYWORD
        End If
        Let is_move be proc match_string with text, "move", 4
        If is_move is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_KEYWORD
        End If
        Let is_loop be proc match_string with text, "loop", 4
        If is_loop is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_KEYWORD
        End If
    End If

    Note: Length 5
    If length is equal to 5:
        Let is_match be proc match_string with text, "match", 5
        If is_match is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_KEYWORD
        End If
        Let is_while be proc match_string with text, "while", 5
        If is_while is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_KEYWORD
        End If
        Let is_const be proc match_string with text, "const", 5
        If is_const is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_KEYWORD
        End If
        Let is_trait be proc match_string with text, "trait", 5
        If is_trait is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_KEYWORD
        End If
        Let is_where be proc match_string with text, "where", 5
        If is_where is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_KEYWORD
        End If
        Let is_async be proc match_string with text, "async", 5
        If is_async is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_KEYWORD
        End If
        Let is_await be proc match_string with text, "await", 5
        If is_await is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_KEYWORD
        End If
        Let is_break be proc match_string with text, "break", 5
        If is_break is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_KEYWORD
        End If
        Let is_crate be proc match_string with text, "crate", 5
        If is_crate is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_KEYWORD
        End If
        Let is_super be proc match_string with text, "super", 5
        If is_super is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_KEYWORD
        End If
    End If

    Note: Length 6
    If length is equal to 6:
        Let is_struct be proc match_string with text, "struct", 6
        If is_struct is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_KEYWORD
        End If
        Let is_return be proc match_string with text, "return", 6
        If is_return is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_KEYWORD
        End If
        Let is_static be proc match_string with text, "static", 6
        If is_static is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_KEYWORD
        End If
        Let is_unsafe be proc match_string with text, "unsafe", 6
        If is_unsafe is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_KEYWORD
        End If
        Let is_extern be proc match_string with text, "extern", 6
        If is_extern is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_KEYWORD
        End If
    End If

    Note: Length 8
    If length is equal to 8:
        Let is_continue be proc match_string with text, "continue", 8
        If is_continue is equal to 1:
            Return TOKEN_KEYWORD
        End If
    End If

    Return TOKEN_IDENTIFIER
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Lexing Functions
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Scans an identifier or keyword. The caller has verified the first
byte is is_alpha. This routine consumes the longest run of
is_alphanumeric bytes and then defers to classify_keyword for the
TOKEN_KEYWORD/TOKEN_IDENTIFIER decision.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Snapshots start_pos = position. While loop calls peek_char; EOF (0)
or non-alphanumeric breaks. Computes length = (final position) -
start_pos and lexeme = source + start_pos. classify_keyword returns
the token type; the lexeme bytes are copied into a StringCore via
create_string_from_buffer, then a new token is allocated.
@End Implementation
Process called "lex_identifier" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Lex identifier or keyword

    Let source be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 0
    Let position be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16
    Let start_pos be position

    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let char be proc peek_char from lexer
        If char is equal to 0:
            Break
        End If

        Let is_alnum be proc is_alphanumeric from char
        If is_alnum is not equal to 1:
            Break
        End If

        proc advance_char from lexer
    End While

    Let new_position be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16
    Let length be new_position minus start_pos
    Let text be source plus start_pos

    Let token_type be proc classify_keyword with text, length
    Let value be proc create_string_from_buffer from StringCore with text, length
    Let token be proc create_token with token_type, value, 0, 0

    Return token
End Process

@Reasoning:
Scans a Rust numeric literal. Rust admits decimal, hex (0x), octal
(0o), binary (0b) integer forms; floats with optional decimal point
and 'e'/'E' exponent with optional sign; and type suffixes
(i8/i16/i32/i64/i128, u8/u16/u32/u64/u128, f32/f64) plus underscore
digit separators anywhere in the digit run. The complete lexeme
(prefix + digits + decimal + exponent + suffix) is preserved verbatim
in the token's value so later passes can parse the actual number.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Snapshots start_pos and reads source_length. First byte '0' triggers
a prefix probe: 'x' enters a hex-digits + underscore loop; 'o' enters
an octal-only (0..7) + underscore loop; 'b' enters a binary-only
(0,1) + underscore loop. If no prefix matched, falls through to the
generic decimal scan. The decimal scan tracks has_dot to forbid two
decimal points; consumes 'e' as exponent marker followed by optional
'+/-' and digits; consumes '_' as digit separator. After the body,
suffix dispatch: 'i'/'u'/'f' each consume their letter and any
trailing digit run (covers i32, u64, f64, etc.). Final token records
the full lexeme as a copied StringCore under TOKEN_NUMBER.
@End Implementation
Process called "lex_number" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Lex integer or float literal

    @Reasoning:
    Rust supports: decimal, hex (0x), octal (0o), binary (0b), floats with exponents.
    Handle all number formats with proper suffix support (i32, u64, f64, etc).
    @End Reasoning

    Let source be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 0
    Let position be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16
    Let start_pos be position
    Let source_length be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 8

    Let char be proc peek_char from lexer

    Note: Check for hex, octal, or binary prefix
    If char is equal to 48:  Note: 0
        proc advance_char from lexer
        Let next_char be proc peek_char from lexer

        Note: Hexadecimal 0x
        If next_char is equal to 120:  Note: x
            proc advance_char from lexer
            While 1 is equal to 1:
                Let hex_char be proc peek_char from lexer
                If hex_char is equal to 0:
                    Break
                End If
                Let is_hex be proc is_hex_digit from hex_char
                If is_hex is not equal to 1:
                    If hex_char is not equal to 95:  Note: Underscore separator
                        Break
                    End If
                End If
                proc advance_char from lexer
            End While
        End If

        Note: Octal 0o
        If next_char is equal to 111:  Note: o
            proc advance_char from lexer
            While 1 is equal to 1:
                Let octal_char be proc peek_char from lexer
                If octal_char is equal to 0:
                    Break
                End If
                If octal_char is greater than or equal to 48:
                    If octal_char is less than or equal to 55:  Note: 0-7
                        proc advance_char from lexer
                    Otherwise:
                        If octal_char is equal to 95:  Note: Underscore
                            proc advance_char from lexer
                        Otherwise:
                            Break
                        End If
                    End If
                    Otherwise:
                    Break
                End If
            End While
        End If

        Note: Binary 0b
        If next_char is equal to 98:  Note: b
            proc advance_char from lexer
            While 1 is equal to 1:
                Let bin_char be proc peek_char from lexer
                If bin_char is equal to 0:
                    Break
                End If
                If bin_char is equal to 48:  Note: 0
                    proc advance_char from lexer
                Otherwise:
                    If bin_char is equal to 49:  Note: 1
                        proc advance_char from lexer
                    Otherwise:
                        If bin_char is equal to 95:  Note: Underscore
                            proc advance_char from lexer
                        Otherwise:
                            Break
                        End If
                    End If
                End If
            End While
        End If
    End If

    Note: Regular decimal or float
    Let has_dot be 0
    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let digit_char be proc peek_char from lexer
        If digit_char is equal to 0:
            Break
        End If

        Let is_digit_result be proc is_digit from digit_char
        If is_digit_result is equal to 1:
            proc advance_char from lexer
        Otherwise:
            Note: Decimal point
            If digit_char is equal to 46:
                If has_dot is equal to 0:
                    Set has_dot to 1
                    proc advance_char from lexer
                Otherwise:
                    Break
                End If
            Otherwise:
                Note: Exponent e
                If digit_char is equal to 101:
                    proc advance_char from lexer
                    Let exp_char be proc peek_char from lexer
                    If exp_char is equal to 43:
                        proc advance_char from lexer
                    End If
                    If exp_char is equal to 45:
                        proc advance_char from lexer
                    End If
                Otherwise:
                    Note: Underscore separator
                    If digit_char is equal to 95:
                        proc advance_char from lexer
                    Otherwise:
                        Break
                    End If
                End If
            End If
        End If
    End While

    Note: Skip type suffix (i32, u64, f64, etc.)
    Let suffix_char be proc peek_char from lexer
    If suffix_char is equal to 105:  Note: i
        proc advance_char from lexer
        Note: Skip digits for i8, i16, i32, i64, i128
        While 1 is equal to 1:
            Let s_char be proc peek_char from lexer
            Let is_d be proc is_digit from s_char
            If is_d is not equal to 1:
                Break
            End If
            proc advance_char from lexer
        End While
    End If
    If suffix_char is equal to 117:  Note: u
        proc advance_char from lexer
        Note: Skip digits for u8, u16, u32, u64, u128
        While 1 is equal to 1:
            Set s_char to proc peek_char from lexer
            Set is_d to proc is_digit from s_char
            If is_d is not equal to 1:
                Break
            End If
            proc advance_char from lexer
        End While
    End If
    If suffix_char is equal to 102:  Note: f
        proc advance_char from lexer
        Note: Skip digits for f32, f64
        While 1 is equal to 1:
            Set s_char to proc peek_char from lexer
            Set is_d to proc is_digit from s_char
            If is_d is not equal to 1:
                Break
            End If
            proc advance_char from lexer
        End While
    End If

    Let new_position be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16
    Let length be new_position minus start_pos
    Let text be source plus start_pos
    Let value be proc create_string_from_buffer from StringCore with text, length
    Let token be proc create_token with TOKEN_NUMBER, value, 0, 0

    Return token
End Process

@Reasoning:
Scans an ordinary Rust string literal "...". Caller has verified the
first byte is '"'. Escape sequences (\n, \t, \", \\, \xNN, \u{NNNN})
are consumed structurally as backslash + one byte; semantic
interpretation belongs to a later pass. Unterminated strings (EOF
before closing quote) leave the lexeme spanning to EOF.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Snapshots start_pos. Consumes the opening '"'. Loop body: EOF (0)
breaks. Backslash (92) consumes both itself and the following byte
(skip escape payload). Closing '"' (34) consumes and breaks.
Otherwise consumes one byte. Materialises the lexeme as a StringCore
via create_string_from_buffer and emits TOKEN_STRING.
@End Implementation

@Security_Scope:
Untrusted source; EOF check prevents unbounded scanning on
unterminated literals.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "lex_string" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Lex string literal

    Let source be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 0
    Let position be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16
    Let start_pos be position

    Note: Skip opening quote
    proc advance_char from lexer

    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let char be proc peek_char from lexer
        If char is equal to 0:
            Break
        End If

        Note: Escape sequence
        If char is equal to 92:  Note: Backslash
            proc advance_char from lexer
            proc advance_char from lexer  Note: Skip escaped character
        Otherwise:
            Note: Closing quote
            If char is equal to 34:  Note: "
                proc advance_char from lexer
                Break
            Otherwise:
                proc advance_char from lexer
            End If
        End If
    End While

    Let new_position be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16
    Let length be new_position minus start_pos
    Let text be source plus start_pos
    Let value be proc create_string_from_buffer from StringCore with text, length
    Let token be proc create_token with TOKEN_STRING, value, 0, 0

    Return token
End Process

@Reasoning:
Scans a Rust character literal 'c'. Caller has verified the leading
quote and verified that what follows is NOT a lifetime (a leading
alpha after the quote would have been routed to lex_lifetime by the
dispatcher in tokenize). The body is either one byte or a backslash
escape; the closing quote is consumed unconditionally.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Snapshots start_pos. Consumes opening quote. If next byte is
backslash (92) consumes two bytes (the escape payload); otherwise
one byte. Then consumes the closing quote unconditionally - malformed
literals (closing quote missing) will absorb whatever byte follows,
which is acceptable because the parser will surface a downstream
diagnostic. Emits TOKEN_CHAR with the full lexeme.
@End Implementation
Process called "lex_char" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Lex character literal

    Let source be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 0
    Let position be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16
    Let start_pos be position

    Note: Skip opening quote
    proc advance_char from lexer

    Let char be proc peek_char from lexer
    If char is equal to 92:  Note: Escape sequence
        proc advance_char from lexer
        proc advance_char from lexer
    Otherwise:
        proc advance_char from lexer
    End If

    Note: Skip closing quote
    proc advance_char from lexer

    Let new_position be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16
    Let length be new_position minus start_pos
    Let text be source plus start_pos
    Let value be proc create_string_from_buffer from StringCore with text, length
    Let token be proc create_token with TOKEN_CHAR, value, 0, 0

    Return token
End Process

@Reasoning:
Scans a Rust lifetime annotation ('a, 'static, '_) which is
syntactically a single quote followed by an identifier rather than a
quoted character. The dispatcher in tokenize already distinguishes
lifetimes from char literals by peek_ahead(1) being is_alpha; this
routine assumes that contract.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Snapshots start_pos. Consumes the opening single quote. Loops
consuming is_alphanumeric bytes until a non-identifier byte or EOF
is hit. Materialises the lexeme (including the leading apostrophe)
as a StringCore and emits TOKEN_LIFETIME.
@End Implementation
Process called "lex_lifetime" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Lex lifetime annotation ('a, 'static)

    Let source be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 0
    Let position be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16
    Let start_pos be position

    Note: Skip '
    proc advance_char from lexer

    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let char be proc peek_char from lexer
        If char is equal to 0:
            Break
        End If

        Let is_alnum be proc is_alphanumeric from char
        If is_alnum is not equal to 1:
            Break
        End If

        proc advance_char from lexer
    End While

    Let new_position be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16
    Let length be new_position minus start_pos
    Let text be source plus start_pos
    Let value be proc create_string_from_buffer from StringCore with text, length
    Let token be proc create_token with TOKEN_LIFETIME, value, 0, 0

    Return token
End Process

@Reasoning:
Scans the longest matching operator at the cursor. Rust's operator
set includes single-char (+, -, etc.), two-char compound (::, ->,
=>, +=, ==, &&, ||, ..), and three-char operators (..=, <<=, >>=).
This routine consumes the first byte, then conditionally consumes
the second based on the (first, next) pair, and for '..' / '<<' /
'>>' optionally consumes a third '=' for inclusive-range or
shift-assign forms. The resulting span is emitted as a single
TOKEN_OPERATOR.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Snapshots start_pos, reads char and advances. Reads next_char. A
cascade of per-first-byte branches consumes additional bytes for
each recognised compound form: ':'+':' => '::'; '-'+'>' => '->';
'-'+'=' => '-='; '='+'>' => '=>'; '='+'=' => '=='; '.'+'.' =>
'..', and if a third '=' is present consumes that for '..='. The
arithmetic compounds '+=' '*=' '/=' '%=' follow the same pattern.
Bitwise: '&'+'=' '&&' '|=' '||' '^='. Comparison: '!=' '<=' '>=' and
shift '<<' / '>>' (with optional '=' third byte for '<<=' / '>>=').
The complete operator span is materialised as a TOKEN_OPERATOR.
@End Implementation
Process called "lex_operator" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Lex operator token

    Let source be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 0
    Let position be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16
    Let start_pos be position

    Let char be proc peek_char from lexer
    proc advance_char from lexer

    Note: Two-character operators
    Let next_char be proc peek_char from lexer

    Note: ::, ->, =>, .., +=, -=, *=, /=, %=, &=, |=, ^=, ==, !=, <=, >=, <<, >>, &&, ||, ..=
    If char is equal to 58:  Note: :
        If next_char is equal to 58:  Note: ::
            proc advance_char from lexer
        End If
    End If
    If char is equal to 45:  Note: -
        If next_char is equal to 62:  Note: ->
            proc advance_char from lexer
        End If
        If next_char is equal to 61:  Note: -=
            proc advance_char from lexer
        End If
    End If
    If char is equal to 61:  Note: =
        If next_char is equal to 62:  Note: =>
            proc advance_char from lexer
        End If
        If next_char is equal to 61:  Note: ==
            proc advance_char from lexer
        End If
    End If
    If char is equal to 46:  Note: .
        If next_char is equal to 46:  Note: ..
            proc advance_char from lexer
            Let third_char be proc peek_char from lexer
            If third_char is equal to 61:  Note: ..=
                proc advance_char from lexer
            End If
        End If
    End If
    If char is equal to 43:  Note: +
        If next_char is equal to 61:  Note: +=
            proc advance_char from lexer
        End If
    End If
    If char is equal to 42:  Note: *
        If next_char is equal to 61:  Note: *=
            proc advance_char from lexer
        End If
    End If
    If char is equal to 47:  Note: /
        If next_char is equal to 61:  Note: /=
            proc advance_char from lexer
        End If
    End If
    If char is equal to 37:  Note: %
        If next_char is equal to 61:  Note: %=
            proc advance_char from lexer
        End If
    End If
    If char is equal to 38:  Note: &
        If next_char is equal to 61:  Note: &=
            proc advance_char from lexer
        End If
        If next_char is equal to 38:  Note: &&
            proc advance_char from lexer
        End If
    End If
    If char is equal to 124:  Note: |
        If next_char is equal to 61:  Note: |=
            proc advance_char from lexer
        End If
        If next_char is equal to 124:  Note: ||
            proc advance_char from lexer
        End If
    End If
    If char is equal to 94:  Note: ^
        If next_char is equal to 61:  Note: ^=
            proc advance_char from lexer
        End If
    End If
    If char is equal to 33:  Note: !
        If next_char is equal to 61:  Note: !=
            proc advance_char from lexer
        End If
    End If
    If char is equal to 60:  Note: <
        If next_char is equal to 61:  Note: <=
            proc advance_char from lexer
        End If
        If next_char is equal to 60:  Note: <<
            proc advance_char from lexer
            Set third_char to proc peek_char from lexer
            If third_char is equal to 61:  Note: <<=
                proc advance_char from lexer
            End If
        End If
    End If
    If char is equal to 62:  Note: >
        If next_char is equal to 61:  Note: >=
            proc advance_char from lexer
        End If
        If next_char is equal to 62:  Note: >>
            proc advance_char from lexer
            Set third_char to proc peek_char from lexer
            If third_char is equal to 61:  Note: >>=
                proc advance_char from lexer
            End If
        End If
    End If

    Let new_position be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16
    Let length be new_position minus start_pos
    Let text be source plus start_pos
    Let value be proc create_string_from_buffer from StringCore with text, length
    Let token be proc create_token with TOKEN_OPERATOR, value, 0, 0

    Return token
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Main Tokenization
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Drives lexing of the entire source into the lexer's tokens list.
Implements first-byte dispatch with two specialised disambiguations:
'/' may be either a division operator or the start of a comment (//
or /*); '\'' may be either a character literal or a lifetime
annotation depending on whether the byte at position+1 is alphabetic.
'#' may begin an attribute (#[...]) or an inner attribute (#![...]).
After the source is exhausted a TOKEN_EOF is appended so the parser
can detect end-of-input without checking list size.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads tokens handle once. Outer loop: skip_whitespace then peek_char;
EOF (0) breaks. '/' (47) inspects source+position+1 directly (cheaper
than calling peek_ahead): '//' delegates to skip_line_comment, '/*'
delegates to skip_block_comment, otherwise falls through to operator
handling. is_alpha -> lex_identifier (push, continue). is_digit ->
lex_number (push, continue). '"' (34) -> lex_string. '\'' (39):
inspect next byte; is_alpha -> lex_lifetime, otherwise lex_char.
'#' (35): scan to ']' and emit TOKEN_ATTRIBUTE with full lexeme.
Otherwise: operator-byte test populates is_operator_char; if set,
lex_operator. Otherwise symbol-byte test ((, ), {, }, [, ], comma,
semicolon) emits a single-byte TOKEN_SYMBOL. Anything else is
silently skipped by a bare advance_char so the lexer never stalls.
At end, push a TOKEN_EOF with empty string value.
@End Implementation

@Security_Scope:
Untrusted source; every unrecognised-byte path consumes at least one
byte so the lexer cannot spin on malformed input.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "tokenize" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Tokenize entire source into tokens

    @Reasoning:
    Main lexer loop. Skip whitespace and comments, then dispatch to
    appropriate lexing function based on character type.
    @End Reasoning

    Let tokens be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 24

    While 1 is equal to 1:
        proc skip_whitespace from lexer

        Let char be proc peek_char from lexer
        If char is equal to 0:
            Break
        End If

        Note: Comments
        If char is equal to 47:  Note: /
            Let position be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16
            Let source be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 0
            Let next_char be proc memory_get_byte from Layout with source, position plus 1

            If next_char is equal to 47:  Note: //
                proc skip_line_comment from lexer
                Continue
            End If

            If next_char is equal to 42:  Note: /*
                proc skip_block_comment from lexer
                Continue
            End If
        End If

        Let token be 0

        Note: Identifier or keyword
        Let is_alpha_result be proc is_alpha from char
        If is_alpha_result is equal to 1:
            Set token to proc lex_identifier from lexer
            proc push from List with tokens, token
            Continue
        End If

        Note: Number
        Let is_digit_result be proc is_digit from char
        If is_digit_result is equal to 1:
            Set token to proc lex_number from lexer
            proc push from List with tokens, token
            Continue
        End If

        Note: String literal
        If char is equal to 34:  Note: "
            Set token to proc lex_string from lexer
            proc push from List with tokens, token
            Continue
        End If

        Note: Character literal or lifetime
        If char is equal to 39:  Note: '
            Set position to proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16
            Set source to proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 0
            Set next_char to proc memory_get_byte from Layout with source, position plus 1

            Note: Lifetime if followed by alpha
            Let is_next_alpha be proc is_alpha from next_char
            If is_next_alpha is equal to 1:
                Set token to proc lex_lifetime from lexer
            Otherwise:
                Set token to proc lex_char from lexer
            End If

            proc push from List with tokens, token
            Continue
        End If

        Note: Attribute
        If char is equal to 35:  Note: #
            Set position to proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16
            Set source to proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 0
            Let start_pos be position

            proc advance_char from lexer
            Set next_char to proc peek_char from lexer

            Note: Inner attribute #!
            If next_char is equal to 33:  Note: !
                proc advance_char from lexer
            End If

            Note: Skip [...]
            If next_char is equal to 91:  Note: [
                proc advance_char from lexer
                While 1 is equal to 1:
                    Let attr_char be proc peek_char from lexer
                    If attr_char is equal to 0:
                        Break
                    End If
                    If attr_char is equal to 93:  Note: ]
                        proc advance_char from lexer
                        Break
                    End If
                    proc advance_char from lexer
                End While
            End If

            Let new_position be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16
            Let length be new_position minus start_pos
            Let text be source plus start_pos
            Let value be proc create_string_from_buffer from StringCore with text, length
            Set token to proc create_token with TOKEN_ATTRIBUTE, value, 0, 0
            proc push from List with tokens, token
            Continue
        End If

        Note: Macro invocation (identifier followed by !)
        Let is_operator_char be 0
        Note: Operators: + - * / % = < > ! bitwise and | bitwise xor : . ? ;
        If char is equal to 43:  Note: +
            Set is_operator_char to 1
        End If
        If char is equal to 45:  Note: -
            Set is_operator_char to 1
        End If
        If char is equal to 42:  Note: *
            Set is_operator_char to 1
        End If
        If char is equal to 47:  Note: /
            Set is_operator_char to 1
        End If
        If char is equal to 37:  Note: %
            Set is_operator_char to 1
        End If
        If char is equal to 61:  Note: =
            Set is_operator_char to 1
        End If
        If char is equal to 60:  Note: <
            Set is_operator_char to 1
        End If
        If char is equal to 62:  Note: >
            Set is_operator_char to 1
        End If
        If char is equal to 33:  Note: !
            Set is_operator_char to 1
        End If
        If char is equal to 38:  Note: &
            Set is_operator_char to 1
        End If
        If char is equal to 124:  Note: |
            Set is_operator_char to 1
        End If
        If char is equal to 94:  Note: ^
            Set is_operator_char to 1
        End If
        If char is equal to 58:  Note: :
            Set is_operator_char to 1
        End If
        If char is equal to 46:  Note: .
            Set is_operator_char to 1
        End If
        If char is equal to 63:  Note: ?
            Set is_operator_char to 1
        End If

        If is_operator_char is equal to 1:
            Set token to proc lex_operator from lexer
            proc push from List with tokens, token
            Continue
        End If

        Note: Symbols: ( ) { } [ ] , ;
        Let is_symbol be 0
        If char is equal to 40:  Note: (
            Set is_symbol to 1
        End If
        If char is equal to 41:  Note: )
            Set is_symbol to 1
        End If
        If char is equal to 123:  Note: {
            Set is_symbol to 1
        End If
        If char is equal to 125:  Note: }
            Set is_symbol to 1
        End If
        If char is equal to 91:  Note: [
            Set is_symbol to 1
        End If
        If char is equal to 93:  Note: ]
            Set is_symbol to 1
        End If
        If char is equal to 44:  Note: ,
            Set is_symbol to 1
        End If
        If char is equal to 59:  Note: ;
            Set is_symbol to 1
        End If

        If is_symbol is equal to 1:
            Set position to proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16
            Set source to proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 0
            proc advance_char from lexer
            Set new_position to proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 16
            Set length to new_position minus position
            Set text to source plus position
            Set value to proc create_string_from_buffer from StringCore with text, length
            Set token to proc create_token with TOKEN_SYMBOL, value, 0, 0
            proc push from List with tokens, token
            Continue
        End If

        Note: Unknown character, skip it
        proc advance_char from lexer
    End While

    Note: Add EOF token
    Let eof_value be proc create_string_from_literal from StringCore with ""
    Let eof_token be proc create_token with TOKEN_EOF, eof_value, 0, 0
    proc push from List with tokens, eof_token

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Accessor for the parsed token list. The caller must not free the
returned list directly; ownership remains with the lexer. The list
is appropriate for read-only iteration; mutation is undefined.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Single memory_get_int64 from offset 24. Returns the borrowed list
handle.
@End Implementation
Process called "get_tokens" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Get token list from lexer

    Let tokens be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 24
    Return tokens
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Helper Functions
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Byte-equal compare specialised to the keyword-bucket use case in
classify_keyword. The pattern is passed as a Runa String literal but
read byte-by-byte alongside the source span; both are required to be
exactly 'length' bytes (caller ensures this via length bucketing).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Loop 0..length: each iteration reads text[i] and pattern[i] via
memory_get_byte and returns 0 on mismatch. Falls off the loop with
return 1 on full match.
@End Implementation
Process called "match_string" takes text as Integer, pattern as String, length as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Match string against pattern

    Let i be 0
    While i is less than length:
        Let text_char be proc memory_get_byte from Layout with text, i
        Let pattern_char be proc memory_get_byte from Layout with pattern, i

        If text_char is not equal to pattern_char:
            Return 0
        End If

        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Return 1
End Process
